"“Route an immediate records-preservation request through MPD dispatch to Hartwell. Preserve the local-challenge record for 07:46 through 07:48:30, the controlled-door and staff-route logs, exterior and interior access-camera records, the inspection position, and any record that identifies the challenge serial and the person presenting or receiving it.”\n\nMercer stepped forward half a pace.\n\nOrtiz’s raised hand stopped him again.\n\nJulie kept speaking to the camera.\n\n“The request is not an accusation that Senator Sterling possessed the signer. It is not a claim that the black case contained it. It is a request to preserve the records needed to determine those facts later. Masking Window Two begins at 07:48. I do not know what it does. Phase B has an authorization deadline at 07:49. I do not know what action Phase B authorizes. Relay K-seventeen access was not confirmed in the 07:08 record. The substantive message blocks remain encrypted.”\n\nOrtiz studied her for one second.\n\n“You understand I am not validating any of that.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“I am documenting a claim from a person named in an armed-insider alert.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“And you are asking police to contact a protected federal briefing site while you are under apprehension.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe answer did not make him trust her.\n\nIt made the request precise enough to route.\n\nOrtiz touched his shoulder microphone without taking his eyes from Julie.\n\n“Dispatch, Unit Three. Start an evidentiary-preservation request associated with the Hartwell perimeter incident. Time-sensitive. Requesting hold on local challenge, controlled-door, staff-route, inspection-area, and relevant camera records from zero-seven-forty-six through zero-seven-forty-eight-thirty. Request originates on scene from subject O’Donnell. Record as unverified subject statement. No request for substantive disclosure.”\n\nStatic opened and closed.\n\n“Unit Three, confirm challenge record is claimed to be active now.”\n\n“Affirmative. Claimed window is open now and closes at zero-seven-forty-eight-thirty.”\n\n“Copy. Routing through District watch and Hartwell liaison. Event number follows.”\n\nA sequence of digits came over the radio.\n\nMarcus reached for the paper log.\n\nOrtiz’s voice sharpened. “Sir, hands.”\n\nMarcus stopped with his left hand above the waterproof folder. The movement had already pulled across his ribs. His face tightened beneath the blood-stained dressing above his ear.\n\n“Paper custody log,” he said. “I need to record the dispatch event number.”\n\n“Do not reach until I tell you.”\n\nMarcus returned both hands to view.\n\nJulie saw what the instruction cost him. The log was his primary chronology. Six years ago, he had protected access by letting the official record carry a useful ambiguity. Now an honest officer had stopped him from writing, and he obeyed rather than turn custody into another fight.\n\n“Officer,” Julie said, “the paper log is part of the evidence chain.”\n\n“I heard him.”\n\n“He cannot stand safely.”\n\n“I can see that too.”\n\nOrtiz shifted one step to improve his angle on the passenger area without closing the distance. His body camera moved with him, taking in Marcus, the open passenger door, the aluminum case between his boots, and the waterproof folder against his thigh.\n\n“Use your left hand only,” Ortiz said. “Slowly. Open the folder. Remove only the bound paper log and pen. Nothing else.”\n\nMarcus did exactly that.\n\nThe damaged boot scraped the van floor when he adjusted. His right thigh trembled beneath the gray coveralls. He stopped before the leg failed and balanced the log across the waterproof folder instead of lifting it. Every breath remained shallow.\n\n“State what you are recording,” Ortiz said.\n\n“MPD event number. Time of request. Requesting officer. Stated scope. No transfer.”\n\n“Do it.”\n\nMarcus wrote.\n\nThe pen shook. The words remained legible.\n\n07:46:42.\n\nThe dispatch request existed outside the trio’s own chronology before Hartwell’s event completed.\n\nMercer moved into the open space Ortiz had left between the columns. He stopped at the officer’s boundary.\n\n“Officer Ortiz, Apex Defense Systems asserts ownership and security authority over the classified telemetry case and the electronic module. Both were removed from an accredited facility during an active sabotage event. They require immediate recovery by authorized program personnel.”\n\nOrtiz kept his body toward the trio. “Who is the receiving federal authority?”\n\n“Apex is the designated facility security authority.”\n\n“For Building Three.”\n\n“For the material.”\n\n“That is a claim of ownership. I asked who receives criminal or evidentiary custody.”\n\nMercer’s jaw tightened. “The incident is under joint coordination.”\n\n“Name the agency and receiving officer.”\n\nMercer touched his radio.\n\nBefore he could speak, Vance’s voice came through the open channel, polished and unmistakable.\n\n“The material is classified strategic telemetry under executive recovery authority. O’Donnell’s attempt to direct preservation at Hartwell is continuing hostile target development. Secure both devices before she manipulates another protected system.”\n\nOrtiz looked at Elias’s module.\n\nElias’s hands tightened around it.\n\nJulie saw the officer’s attention change. The object looked worse because Vance had named it as active danger.\n\n“It is offline,” Elias said.\n\n“Do not touch anything,” Ortiz ordered.\n\n“I’m not.”\n\n“What does offline mean?”\n\n“No radio. No network connection. No Hartwell connection. It contains two sealed partitions and a local handling journal.”\n\nMercer said, “He used similar media to capture a protected Northbridge session.”\n\nElias’s fear showed in the speed of his next breath, not in the answer.\n\n“Yes. At Northbridge, it was physically connected to a local audit port under a sponsor exception obtained by deception. It is not connected now. It cannot read Hartwell. It cannot penetrate Hartwell. It cannot identify a certificate across the street.”\n\nOrtiz said, “Then why are you holding it?”\n\n“Because Partition A contains a sealed derivative made before Northbridge. Partition B contains the sealed WSS-four incident package. The board against my body is the original administrator token that distinguishes my replayed deployment identity from my later voluntary actions. Separating them from me without a documented transfer damages the evidence.”\n\n“You are telling me the device is evidence.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Not a tool.”\n\n“It can be both in other conditions. Here, now, it is offline evidence with a local manual marker function.”\n\nOrtiz’s eyes went to Elias’s left thumb.\n\n“What does the button do?”\n\n“It writes a handling event into the enclosure journal. Local input, device time, local hardware state.”\n\n“What does it prove?”\n\n“That I pressed it.”\n\n“What does it prove about Hartwell?”\n\n“Nothing by itself.”\n\nThe answer entered the body-camera record in Elias’s own voice.\n\nA second radio transmission cut across Mercer’s channel. Sarah Chen spoke with the controlled cadence Julie remembered from Room 402B.\n\n“Incident coordination to all Apex personnel at the garage. Metropolitan Police has scene authority. Capture and evidence preservation remain active. No transfer to Apex absent named receiving custody and a documented receipt. Subjects remain under apprehension. Do not allow connection, opening, alteration, or destruction of any media.”\n\nShe had not released them.\n\nShe had denied Vance an undocumented recovery.\n\nVance answered on the same channel. “Executive authority requires immediate isolation of the telemetry.”\n\nChen did not debate him. “Your instruction is preserved. Field force standard and receiving-custody requirement remain unchanged.”\n\nMercer looked at his radio, then at Ortiz.\n\nThe officer had heard both instructions.\n\nSo had the body camera.\n\nJulie turned her head far enough to recover the Hartwell sightline without moving her feet.\n\nThe controlled door remained closed. The lamp above it remained white. The exterior officer stood near the privacy-screen position, one hand at his earpiece. The probable support SUV had not moved.\n\nThe hidden hand remained hidden.\n\nThe dashboard clock changed to 07:47:03.\n\nLess than ninety seconds remained in the Hartwell window.\n\nOrtiz saw her attention shift.\n\n“You said no movement toward the site.”\n\n“We are not moving.”\n\n“Then keep your feet where they are.”\n\n“I will.”\n\nHis radio carried the dispatch event into another channel. A District watch officer repeated the preservation scope. Hartwell security requested the incident basis. Dispatch answered with the known-plate alert, the protected-site proximity, and Julie’s recorded claim. No one endorsed the claim. No one rejected the need to preserve a record during an active police containment.\n\nProcedure moved because later review required something to review.\n\nThe second officer checked the west ramp.\n\n“Unit Three, west vehicle line is still moving. Additional cruiser is entering the outbound gate below.”\n\nMarcus heard it.\n\n“Route exposed,” he said.\n\nOrtiz looked at him. “Do not make a route call.”\n\n“He owns the vehicle decision,” Julie said.\n\n“You own nothing on this scene.”\n\n“The evidence roles still exist whether you recognize them or not.”\n\nOrtiz’s expression hardened.\n\nJulie corrected herself before defiance became the only thing the camera preserved.\n\n“You control the scene. Marcus knows whether the van can move without striking an officer or losing the originals. I need him to state when that becomes impossible.”\n\n“You are not moving the van.”\n\n“If the gate remains physically open, that is an instruction. If the gate becomes physically blocked, it is also the abort condition we established before you reached this level.”\n\nOrtiz studied her.\n\n“You are telling me you will stop when police close the route.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“You are already being told to stop.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe two facts did not merge neatly. Julie had continued observation while obeying the no-advance line. Ortiz had lawful authority to detain her before the Hartwell event finished. She had no lawful authority to keep the scene open.\n\nHe could end it now.\n\nInstead, he said, “The van does not move. You stay where you are. If the route changes, my officer will call it.”\n\nJulie nodded once.\n\nThe dark-overcoat entrant appeared outside Hartwell.\n\nThe controlled door opened only far enough to release one person. The overcoat stepped through, turned sideways while the door closed, and returned along the narrow lane toward the exterior holding position. Both hands were visible above the privacy panel.\n\nEmpty.\n\nJulie raised one finger with her left hand and kept her feet planted.\n\n“07:47:21. Dark-overcoat entrant has returned outside the controlled domain.”\n\nOrtiz pivoted his shoulders without turning his back on the trio. From his angle, the overcoat was visible between the van’s hood and the open side of the garage.\n\n“I see one person outside the door,” he said. “Dark coat.”\n\n“Do not identify the person,” Julie said. “Clothing only.”\n\n“I know how to describe a person.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe correction was deserved.\n\nElias looked at Ortiz. “Permission to enter one manual handling marker with my left thumb. No connection. No partition access.”\n\nOrtiz took one step closer, stopping well outside reach.\n\n“Turn the display toward me without moving the device away from your body.”\n\nElias did. The movement pulled his injured hip out of alignment. He caught himself against the van with one shoulder and kept the module against his torso.\n\nThe small display showed both partition seals and the handling-journal control.\n\nPARTITION A: SEALED / READ-ONLY / INTEGRITY VERIFIED\nPARTITION B: SEALED / WSS-4 CONTROLLER SEAL PRESENT\nDEVICE HANDLING JOURNAL: AVAILABLE\n\n“Press once,” Ortiz said. “Then remove your thumb.”\n\nElias pressed.\n\nHANDLING EVENT 010\nOPERATOR INPUT: MANUAL\n\nNo external image entered the module. No name. No conclusion.\n\nMarcus wrote the observed time and the limitation.\n\nDARK-OVERCOAT PERSON OUTSIDE CONTROLLED DOOR BEFORE ACCEPTED STATE. CLOTHING IDENTIFIER ONLY. MARKER MANUAL. EXTERNAL FACT REQUIRES CORROBORATION.\n\nOrtiz watched the pen stop.\n\n“What does that change?” he asked.\n\nJulie looked at Hartwell.\n\n“It narrows the set at the exact event time. If the challenge completes while that person remains outside, that person is not physically presenting the device at that moment.”\n\nMercer said, “Unless the exterior signal is unrelated.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Or the device was handed off before the person returned.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Or someone already inside presents it.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe possible answer became smaller and less simple at the same time.\n\nJulie did not resist that.\n\n“That is why we need Hartwell’s record,” she said.\n\nThe white lamp remained steady.\n\n07:47:34.\n\nDispatch returned over Ortiz’s radio.\n\n“Unit Three, Hartwell liaison acknowledges preservation request. Security is checking scope and legal authority. No operational detail will be released to the scene.”\n\n“Copy. Request immediate administrative hold pending authority review. Preserve first, disclose later.”\n\n“Relaying.”\n\nThe exterior Hartwell officer moved away from the privacy screen and looked toward the controlled door. The person in the dark overcoat remained at the holding position, body angled toward the support SUV.\n\nThe other two entrants did not reappear.\n\nJulie could no longer see whether either stood beside a reader, a secure cabinet, an aide, or no device at all.\n\nThe lamp changed.\n\nWhite disappeared.\n\nA steady green state replaced it above the controlled door.\n\n07:47:49.\n\n“Green,” Julie said.\n\nOrtiz turned enough to see it.\n\n“Officer observation,” he said into his body camera. “Hartwell-facing controlled-door exterior indicator changed from steady white to steady green at approximately zero-seven-forty-seven-forty-nine. Technical meaning unknown.”\n\nThat sentence mattered more than Julie’s conclusion would have.\n\nElias held still.\n\n“Marker?” he asked.\n\nOrtiz considered the module, the open radio traffic, and the fact that he had just controlled the first entry.\n\n“Same procedure. Once.”\n\nElias’s left thumb moved.\n\nHANDLING EVENT 011\nOPERATOR INPUT: MANUAL\n\nThe module’s local clock existed behind the journal entry. Julie did not ask Elias to read it aloud. The officer’s body camera and dispatch clock were now the stronger independent chronology.\n\nMarcus wrote:\n\nEXTERIOR HARTWELL STATE WHITE TO STEADY GREEN. OFFICER ORTIZ INDEPENDENTLY OBSERVED. TECHNICAL MEANING AND DEVICE SERIAL UNPROVED.\n\nMercer looked toward the lamp.\n\n“The local challenge completed.”\n\n“A local challenge reached an accepted exterior state,” Elias said. “We cannot identify which serial from the lamp.”\n\n“You know which serial was scheduled.”\n\n“We know SSO-NS-zero-zero-four was expected.”\n\n“And now the light is green.”\n\n“Expectation plus a visible state justifies preservation. It does not replace the held log.”\n\nOrtiz said, “Enough technical argument.”\n\nIt was enough.\n\nThe event had occurred inside the predicted window. The office-registered signer remained the expected device. The green state showed that Hartwell’s local challenge process had reached a distinct accepted or complete exterior state.\n\nThe exact serial remained inside Hartwell.\n\nThe human hand remained behind the door.\n\nJulie looked at the dark overcoat standing outside.\n\nAt the moment of acceptance, one observed entrant was excluded from direct presentation. The other two remained possible. So did an internal authorized person. So did a handoff completed behind the screen before entry.\n\nThe witness line had strengthened.\n\nThe carrier line had become more honest.\n\nThe dashboard clock reached 07:48:00.\n\nMasking Window Two began.\n\nNothing visible changed at Hartwell.\n\nNo alarm sounded. No vehicle moved. No screen appeared in Julie’s possession. The pending reconstruction profile remained a name inside the sealed WSS-4 capture, not an action she could see or define.\n\n“Window is open,” Elias said quietly.\n\nOrtiz heard him. “What window?”\n\n“A six-minute interval named in the WSS session. Seven-forty-eight to seven-fifty-four.”\n\n“What happens during it?”\n\n“We do not know.”\n\nVance’s voice entered Mercer’s radio again.\n\n“The preservation request is itself part of O’Donnell’s continuing attempt to map protected authentication. Recover the module before the masking cycle is compromised.”\n\nJulie looked at Mercer.\n\n“He said masking cycle.”\n\nMercer’s expression did not change.\n\nThe words were not proof that Vance controlled the window. They were proof that he had characterized it with a noun more specific than the public record had given Julie.\n\nOrtiz heard that too.\n\nChen’s voice followed.\n\n“Executive statement logged. All personnel maintain current positions. No device connection. No unreceipted transfer. Preserve radio traffic.”\n\nVance did not answer.\n\nMercer looked at Ortiz. “Apex maintains the case and module contain classified material removed from two protected environments. We request they be isolated under police guard pending federal transfer.”\n\n“That is different from handing them to you,” Ortiz said.\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe concession did not make Mercer an ally. It made him a professional choosing a claim he could defend later.\n\nDispatch called Ortiz.\n\n“Unit Three, Hartwell duty security acknowledges the relevant local-challenge and access event record exists. Administrative preservation hold entered pending legal review. Hartwell will not disclose signer serial, certificate chain, presenter identity, challenge content, staff identity, or briefing information over this channel.”\n\nOrtiz answered immediately. “Confirm hold time.”\n\n“Zero-seven-forty-eight-sixteen.”\n\nThe acknowledgment arrived before the challenge window closed.\n\n“Copy,” Ortiz said. “Preserve acknowledgment and routing history under the scene event.”\n\n“Affirmative.”\n\nJulie looked at Elias.\n\n“Safe marker?” he asked Ortiz.\n\nThe officer had already supervised two inputs without a connection, partition change, or unexpected movement.\n\n“One final marker,” Ortiz said. “Same procedure. Then no more device input.”\n\nElias turned the display. His left arm trembled from holding the module against his torso for too long.\n\nHe pressed once.\n\nHANDLING EVENT 012\nOPERATOR INPUT: MANUAL\n\n“Marker proves only my input and local device state,” he said for the body camera. “Hartwell’s acknowledgment exists on police dispatch, not inside this module.”\n\nMarcus recorded the dispatch time, the hold time, and the explicit disclosure refusal. His handwriting deteriorated near the bottom of the line. He did not rewrite it.\n\nThe dashboard clock showed 07:48:19.\n\nThe second officer spoke from the west sightline.\n\n“Unit Three, outbound gate is closing. Cruiser is across the lower lane. Civilian vehicle clearing now.”\n\nMarcus turned his head too quickly toward the mirror.\n\nThe level shifted under him. His left hand caught the door frame. The paper log slid across the waterproof folder and stopped against the case handle.\n\nJulie moved by instinct.\n\nHer right hand left the brace.\n\nPain opened the grip before it formed.\n\nShe stopped herself instead of reaching across the police line.\n\n“Marcus.”\n\nHe closed his eyes once and kept both hands visible.\n\n“Still conscious.”\n\n“Route?”\n\nHe looked through the mirror more slowly.\n\nThe last civilian sedan descended the west ramp. Blue lights reflected against the concrete below. A marked cruiser stood crosswise at the outbound gate, front bumper near the barrier housing. A uniformed officer moved behind it and lowered the manual arm.\n\nPhysical control.\n\nNot exposure.\n\nNot a possible intercept one block away.\n\nThe route was closed.\n\n“West gate blocked,” Marcus said. “Police vehicle and controlled barrier. No evidence-preserving movement available.”\n\nThe clock showed 07:48:24.\n\nJulie felt the old argument rise before anyone spoke it.\n\nThe Hartwell window had six seconds left.\n\nThe accepted state was visible.\n\nThe preservation hold had not yet been confirmed.\n\nPCF-27’s engine was running. The lower gate was blocked. Marcus could not work the pedals normally. Julie could not steer with her right hand. Moving the van would require an officer to jump, a barrier to break, or a civilian lane to become cover.\n\nThe mission line did not become optional because success was close.\n\n“Abort,” Julie said.\n\nMarcus’s left hand came away from the log.\n\nElias removed his thumb from the module control.\n\nJulie faced Ortiz fully.\n\n“The west route is physically controlled. The Hartwell observation mission is over. We will not move the van. We will not approach Hartwell.”\n\nOrtiz’s shoulders lowered by a fraction.\n\n“Turn off the engine.”\n\nJulie looked at the driver’s door. It was closed. The key remained in the ignition where Marcus had reached across to start the van.\n\n“My right hand cannot grip. I can open the driver’s door and turn the key with my left under your instruction.”\n\n“Do it slowly. Left hand only. Keep your right arm against your body.”\n\nJulie lowered her left hand only when he told her.\n\nShe took one step to the driver’s door. The movement placed her nearer the van but no closer to Hartwell. Ortiz moved with her, body camera centered on her hand.\n\nShe opened the door with her left fingers.\n\nThe engine vibration reached through the metal and into her wrist before she touched the key. She leaned across the threshold without putting weight on the injured hand, turned the ignition back with her left thumb and forefinger, and released it.\n\nThe engine stopped.\n\nSilence spread through the level beneath the police radios and distant city traffic.\n\nJulie left the key visible in the ignition.\n\n“Step back,” Ortiz said.\n\nShe returned to the driver-side front quarter and raised her left hand.\n\nHer right wrist settled against her body.\n\n07:48:30.\n\nThe Hartwell window closed.\n\nThe steady green lamp remained visible across the gap. It could not tell them whether the accepted event belonged to SSO-NS-004. It could not tell them who had presented anything. It could not tell them whether the challenge record would survive intact under the hold.\n\nIt was only a state witnessed before the clock closed.\n\nOrtiz said, “Close the log.”\n\nMarcus did.\n\n“Put the pen on the dashboard.”\n\nMarcus placed it where the officer could see it.\n\n“Both hands on the door frame.”\n\nHe obeyed as far as his ribs allowed. The aluminum case remained between his boots. The waterproof folder stayed against his thigh. No hand entered it.\n\nThe second officer returned from the ramp and took position near PCF-27’s rear quarter. He did not touch the van.\n\nOrtiz spoke clearly enough for every body camera and radio on the level.\n\n“Metropolitan Police has scene control. All three subjects are detained pending identification of federal receiving authority and safe evidence-custody procedure. No one opens, connects, alters, or transfers any item. Apex personnel remain outside contact distance. Evidence inventory will begin on camera. Subject separation will not occur until object custody and medical movement are addressed.”\n\nMercer said, “Apex requests immediate protective isolation of the electronics.”\n\n“Request noted.”\n\n“The module may contain active classified communications.”\n\n“It is not connected.”\n\n“That is Elias Thorne’s statement.”\n\n“Yes. It is also what I can observe. You will have an opportunity to state your claim on camera.”\n\nMercer looked at Elias. “Mr. Thorne may be under coercion.”\n\nElias’s face tightened.\n\n“No,” he said.\n\nOrtiz looked at him. “State your name.”\n\n“Elias Michael Thorne.”\n\n“Are you holding that module voluntarily?”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Did Ms. O’Donnell force you to enter the markers I observed?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Are you refusing police custody?”\n\n“I am refusing an undocumented transfer. I will comply with a documented police seizure once you identify the receiving officer, authority, time, object serial, seal condition, and custody purpose.”\n\nOrtiz did not promise him continued possession.\n\n“That procedure may occur,” he said. “It has not occurred yet.”\n\n“Understood.”\n\n"